      <div class="blog-content row">
       <div class="blog-left left">
        <div class="inner">
         <div class="blog-header">
          <div class="title">
           This Wall Might Fall on You
          </div>
          <div class="subtitle">
           The Urban Illusions of Aakash Nihilani
          </div>
          <div class="published_dts">
           Posted on May 11, 2015
          </div>
         </div>
         <div class="f-img-wrap">
          <img src="http://image.marky.com/cgi-bin/image.cgi?uuid=A18E8E68-EC6A-11E4-A8EA-95151B7E1716&amp;image_type=image_645"/>
         </div>
         <div class="caption">
          Aakash Nihilani:
          <i>
           Rainborough
          </i>
          , tape, self-portrait, Brooklyn. Image Source:
          <a href="http://www.aakashnihalani.com/outdoor/">
           Aakash Nihilani
          </a>
         </div>
         <div class="body">
          <p>
           Aakash Nihilani can make a wall fall on you  using only fluorescent tape.
          </p>
          <p>
          </p>
          <p>
           Tape graffiti has been a thing since at least 1989, when Rhode Island art students used tape to depict someone carrying an enormous balloon. Less illegal than its spray-can cousin, taping spread rapidly, and artists now roll out their work around the world.
          </p>
          <p>
          </p>
          <p>
           While most tapers use walls as handy surfaces for picture-making though, New York-based Nihalani uses his prisms to pull the urban fabric into new configurations. Blocks taped on a wall or sidewalk create space in the flatness.
          </p>
          <p>
           <br/>
          </p>
         </div>
         <div class="section-layout">
         </div>
         <div class="jump">
          <p>
           <img alt="Image title" class="fr-fin fr-dib" src="http://image.marky.com/cgi-bin/image.cgi?uuid=CCD1BFBE-EC6A-11E4-A7D8-EB746B8BCC62&amp;image_type=image_645" width="400"/>
          </p>
          <div class="caption">
           Aakash Nihilani:
           <em>
            Blocked
           </em>
           , tape, New Delhi. Image Source:
           <a href="http://www.aakashnihalani.com/outdoor/">
            Aakash Nihilani
           </a>
          </div>
          <p>
           <br/>
          </p>
          <p>
           <strong>
            HOW DOES THIS WORK?
           </strong>
          </p>
          <p>
           <br/>
          </p>
          <p>
           Its all an illusion of course, but if the malleable spaces and colored outlines have you feeling that youve stepped into
           <em>
            Tron
           </em>
           -world, dont be surprised. Nihalanis graphics owe quite a debt to the distinct visual style of early 1980s arcade games like
           <em>
            Tron
           </em>
           . This style comes from a traditional Asian technique for creating the illusion of 3-dimensional space on a 2-dimensional surface. Its commonly used today in computer graphics, and can look wrong.
          </p>
          <iframe allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/VcyCWEsbsPU" width="560">
          </iframe>
          <div class="caption">
           Tron (1982),
           <em>
            The Recognizer and the Bit
           </em>
           , posted on You Tube by PlasmaProd, 2013.
          </div>
          <p>
           <br/>
          </p>
          <p>
           <img alt="Image title" class="fr-fin fr-dib" src="http://image.marky.com/cgi-bin/image.cgi?uuid=6B6198D4-EC6B-11E4-A7D8-FCD41F3B9DCA&amp;image_type=image_645"/>
          </p>
          <div class="caption">
           Zhang Zeduan:
           <em>
            Along the River During the Qingming Festival, detail.
           </em>
           Ink on silk, China, 12th Century. Image Source:
           <a href="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d2/Bianjing_city_gate.JPG">
            Wikimedia
           </a>
          </div>
          <p>
           <br/>
          </p>
          <p>
           <strong>
            THESE LOOK KIND OFOFF.
           </strong>
          </p>
          <p>
           You may notice that Nihalanis parallel lines always stay parallel to each other? This is called axonometry. But anyone whos ever taken a Western drawing class knows that parallel lines get closer together as they recede. This is the mathematical system of linear perspective.
          </p>
          <p>
           <br/>
          </p>
          <p>
           Since its invention in early fifteenth century Italy, perspective has dominated Western art and vision. But might the technique that Andrea Pozzo used to such effect in the seventeenth century, and on which Edgar Mueller still depends, be starting to loosen its grip on our eyes? Bringing axonometry out of the computer, and off of the silken scroll, Aakash Nihalanis slightly off boxes change the way we see the city.
          </p>
          <p>
           <br/>
          </p>
          <p>
           <img alt="Image title" class="fr-fin fr-dib" src="http://image.marky.com/cgi-bin/image.cgi?uuid=871D5932-EC6B-11E4-A7D8-B6D550A99D6E&amp;image_type=image_645" width="400"/>
          </p>
          <div class="caption">
           Aakash Nihilani:
           <em>
            Doorway
           </em>
           , tape, Brooklyn. Image Source:
           <a href="http://www.aakashnihalani.com/outdoor/">
            Aakash Nihilani
           </a>
          </div>
          <p>
           <br/>
          </p>
          <p>
           Want to shake the foundations of Western art? Or just decorate your bedroom wall with a removable design? Below are some videos with ideas to share. Get your tape on!
          </p>
          <p>
           <br/>
          </p>
          <p>
           <strong>
            Videos
           </strong>
          </p>
          <p>
           <br/>
          </p>

            Tape Art (graffiti artists masterclass)

           :
          </p>
          <iframe allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/XSH21d_l-dQ" width="420">
          </iframe>
          <p>

            Daydreamers: Tape art and poetry:
